            "answer_text": "Supposing the letter before is \u201ca\u201d: continue from the downstroke of it up to the top of the downstream of \u201cj\u201d, make the stroke, pen off the paper, finish the word, go back and put the dot. When in extreme hurry, the J will develop a loop as you sweep up to the next letter. The style I learned in the 50s was almost italic. Most of us had atrocious loopy writing based on copperplate. It had been taught in old-fashioned schools. Our new lessons tidied it up a lot, while still being fast enough for the breakneck speed of exam answers. ",
